RESUMO-CV.TEXTO-RESUMO-CV-RH-EN: Jaqueline Galdino Albuquerque Perrelli holds a degree in Nursing from the Federal University of Cearб. She completed her Ph.D. in Neuropsychiatry and Behavioral Sciences, specializing in Psychopathology, at the Federal University of Pernambuco in 2014. Additionally, she conducted postdoctoral research in Epidemiology at the Department of Preventive Medicine at the Federal University of Sгo Paulo, focusing on the mental health profiles of university students through Latent Class Analysis (20192022). From 2008 to 2019, she was a faculty member at the Nursing Division of CAV/UFPE, where she served as coordinator (2017-2019) and led extension projects (MEC/Sesu Call for Proposals 2014) as well as PET projects (2011-2012) addressing the prevention of alcohol and drug use among students. Currently, she is an Associate Professor in the Department of Nursing and the Graduate Nursing Program at the Federal University of Pernambuco. She is also a member of the Ibero-American Network Andorinhas, which focuses on promoting adolescent mental health. She coordinates research projects approved under international cooperation programs, including the CNPq Call for Proposals (Process Number: 443939/2023-3), in partnership with the Porto Nursing School, and the CNPq/MCTI/FNDCT Call No. 22/2024 - Brazil Knowledge Program - Support for Networked Projects with Brazilian Researchers Abroad (Process Number: 45162/2024-4), in collaboration with stfold University College; and the Joint Call No. 02/2024 - PROCAD - Academic Cooperation Support Program - Policies on Drugs, in partnership with the Federal University of Sergipe and the Federal University of Roraima. She also serves as the deputy coordinator of the extension project "Suicide: Lets Talk About It?" and is the vice-leader of the Mental Health Studies Center at UFPE. Furthermore, she is a member of the Alcohol and Other Drugs Study Group (GEAD/UFPE) and a reviewer for prominent national and international journals. Dr. Perrelli supervises undergraduate, masters, and doctoral students. Her research interests include: Nursing and Health Education for the promotion of mental health; Prevention of alcohol and drug abuse in basic and higher education; Womens Mental Health during the Pregnancy-Puerperal Cycle; Validation Studies; and Mental Health Literacy.
